==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term/t|la|aberrātus}}, perfect passive participle of {{term/t|la|aberrō||wander, stray or deviate from}}, formed from {{term|ab||from, away from|lang=la}} + {{term/t|la|errō||stray}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.ə.ɹeɪt/}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|aberrat|ing}}

# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To [[go astray]]; to [[diverge]]; to [[deviate]] (from); deviate from. {{defdate|Mid 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=4}}</ref>
#* {{rfdate}} De Quincey
#*: Their own defective and '''aberrating''' vision.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[distort]]; to cause [[aberration]] of. {{defdate|Late 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

====Usage notes====
* {{sense|transitive}} Chiefly used as [[aberrated]].

